{"post_stream":{"posts":[{"id":3561341,"name":"Atharva Mishra","username":"PyDev19","avatar_template":"/user_avatar/www.chiefdelphi.com/pydev19/{size}/253548_2.png","created_at":"2025-03-19T01:17:23.696Z","cooked":"<p>My team and I are programing an elevator for this years challenge but we keep running into issues regarding the elevator staying in place after we move it to a setpoint using PIDs.</p>
<p>The way we are moving the elevator involves using the encoder values as setpoints for the <span class="abbreviation">PID<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Proportional Integral Derivative"></template></span> and this works great in moving the elevator but when we try feedforward we need velocity values. How can we tune the feedforward in this situation?</p>
<p>This is how we calculate PIDs for moving our elevator and we use the PIDController class provided by WPILib, it uses setpoints of encoder values of the relative encoders of the Neo and SparkMaxes.</p>
<pre><code class="lang-auto">    private double calculate_pid(double setpoint) {
        double output = pid_controller.calculate(get_height(), setpoint);
        output = MathUtil.clamp(output, -1.0, 1.0);

        SmartDashboard.putNumber("Elevator PID", pid_controller.calculate(get_height(), setpoint));

        return output;
    }
</code></pre>
<p>To keep the elevator in place after moving it there we have a function called stop that runs everytime the elevator isn’t moving. This is the definition:</p>
<pre><code class="lang-auto">    public void stop() {
        double num = elevatorFF.calculate(get_height());

        right_motor.set(-num);
        left_motor.set(num);

        SmartDashboard.putNumber("Elevator Feedforward", num);
    }
</code></pre>
<p>get height is just a function that returns the current encoder value of the motor controlling the elevator. However, the feed forward expects a velocity value which we don’t know how to get in our current setup. Thanks in advanced.</p>","post_number":1,"post_type":1,"posts_count":6,"updated_at":"2025-03-19T01:17:23.696Z","reply_count":0,"reply_to_post_number":null,"quote_count":0,"incoming_link_count":35,"reads":141,"readers_count":140,"score":198.2,"yours":false,"topic_id":496163,"topic_slug":"how-should-i-go-about-tuning-a-feedforward-for-our-elevator","display_username":"Atharva Mishra","primary_group_name":null,"flair_name":null,"flair_url":null,"flair_bg_color":null,"flair_color":null,"flair_group_id":null,"badges_granted":[],"version":1,"can_edit":false,"can_delete":false,"can_recover":false,"can_see_hidden_post":true,"can_wiki":false,"read":true,"user_title":null,"bookmarked":false,"actions_summary":[],"moderator":false,"admin":false,"staff":false,"user_id":74081,"hidden":false,"trust_level":1,"deleted_at":null,"user_deleted":false,"edit_reason":null,"can_view_edit_history":true,"wiki":false,"user_custom_fields":{"user_field_4":"8816 Supreme Chancelor"},"post_url":"/t/how-should-i-go-about-tuning-a-feedforward-for-our-elevator/496163/1","reactions":[],"current_user_reaction":null,"reaction_users_count":0,"current_user_used_main_reaction":false,"can_accept_answer":false,"can_unaccept_answer":false,"accepted_answer":false,"topic_accepted_answer":null},{"id":3561355,"name":"Sai 3035","username":"luckys301","avatar_template":"/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/l/dec6dc/{size}.png","created_at":"2025-03-19T01:28:17.451Z","cooked":"<p>An easy way to help counteract gravity is to consistently give the motor power on top of what your pid calculates by using calculate_pid()+ gravity_constant.<br>
The way to calculate the gravity constant would be to make your <span class="abbreviation">PID<template class="tooltiptext" data-text="Proportional Integral Derivative"></template></span> 0, and manually move the elevator up while setting a constant motor power. You will increase the power if the elevator falls, and decrease it if it moves up. The best value is when the elevator neither goes up nor down.<br>
